{"key":"processedPost-11985135","value":{"id":11985135,"first":11980537,"last":11985135,"when":1265606277,"utime":"02/08/10 07:17 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>myconoob said:</b><br />and i would like to point out that condensation occurs when warm moist air comes in contact with a cold surface not the other way around <br /></blockquote><br /><br />You're half right.&nbsp; In the winter, condensation forms on the warm side of a glass window, and in the summer, condensation forms on the warm side of a glass of iced tea, which is the outside surface of the glass.<br /><br />However, dew forms on the ground early in the morning when the air cools to the dewpoint. Dew doesn't form during the day when the air is warmer than the ground. This is what's happening with your substrate.&nbsp; If it's excessive, it can stunt the mycelium.<br />RR","title":"Re: dew!?!?!?!?","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}